metadata.name: Miniscapes #85
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Microgravity #573
metadata.description:
Microgravity is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

Scale symmetry of abstract semiliquid forms.

Click on a section of the image to explore deeper.
- Use keys [0-9] to change the detail level.
- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "R" key to reset the coordinates.

metadata.name: Force projection (Unrooted 230802) #19
metadata.description:
Structure of unknown origin, purpose unclear, aka Spotato X
Crossbreed between the universe of Force projection (Compound) and the isoverse

One of 128 generative geometry generators by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
Part of the isoverse

keyboard:
'a' : toggle auto renew, off -> 10s
'r' : new slice
'n' : new iteration with the same features
'l' : new lighting
's' : save image (in fullscreen mode)

mouse:
top left corner: new slice
top right corner: new iteration with the same features
bottom left corner: toggle auto renew, off -> 10s
bottom right corner: new lighting

Mainly targeted to desktop exploration. Performance may vary depending on platform, check before minting. Thumbnail is not representative of the full experience.

metadata.name: Grove #94
metadata.description:
A generative, impressionist painting of a small grove of trees in one of the four seasons. In spring and summer, flowers bloom in the meadow. A rare variation will create a charcoal drawing on white or black paper. Super rare will create a lighted winter scene that may have a moon behind the tree.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press 's' to save a screenshot at any point. Image size is 1400x1082px.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 3,000 px.

On the paintings only, adding '&bg=true' will stop the painting after the background. Adding '&size=3000&bg=true' will give you a nice desktop background! 

Common Features:
- About 12-14 trees
- One of the four seasons
- One of 12 highlight color tints
- One of 12 shadow color tints
- Varying levels of distance haze
- Varying max brush sizes
- Varying amount of colors in the strokes

Less Common
- 15% chance of a charcoal drawing
- 50% chance it to be a dark winter scene

Rare
- Winter drawing with lights on the tree

Super Rare
- Winter drawing with a moon behind the tree

metadata.name: fxPottery #85
metadata.description:
Pottery stands as one of humanity's earliest and most enduring inventions, a testament to our innate desire to craft and create. This project explores the timeless art of pottery through the lens of interactive generative art. In this artwork powered by fxhash, virtual ceramics, shaped by diverse artistic hands, come to life and are shared with the world.

This interactive pottery sim was written from scratch using vanilla JS and webgl shaders. A range of parameters are included to control the final scene and image via the fx params interface.

This artwork is part of the fxhackathon 2023 where artists were challenged to create projects using the interactive fx(params) system.

Standalone Controls

Use mouse or touch to control view
1 - Toggle Edit Mode
2 - Toggle WASD Free Cam
3 - Toggle Frame
4 - Save HD Image

Credits

Code and Outputs are Copyright 2023 Frank Force
Hash without Sine - MIT License - Copyright (c)2014 David Hoskins
Thank you to Inigo Quilez for 3D rendering articles and demos

metadata.name: tr4ns4ctions #7
metadata.description:
Tr4ns4ctions is a series of real-time animations that use pixels to create an abstraction of the movement of values. The pixels are constantly rearranging, being transferred from offer to taker, liquify, appear and disappear. They are forming endless compositions, sometimes intransparent or with strange spins.

The level of abstraction has been set to a 2x pixel size and the color palette of the NES with 12 different color modes. 16 pixel patterns serve as the fundamental building blocks and a simplex noise field determines the direction of movement.

click || space => pause/unpause

View all tr4ns4ctions at https://tr4ns4ctions.com

Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #206
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: fx(haish) / the Generator #28
metadata.description:
fx(haish) is my contribution to #fxhashturnsone
fx(haish) is not a finished product
fx(haish) is a co-creation experiment
fx(haish) is a fun exploration of a mixed GenAI process

fx(haish) is my Happy Birthday to fx(hash). 

Have fun, collectors!


// HOW TO PARTICIPATE

Step 1. Mint or collect “fx(haish) - the Generator”
Step 2. Visit https://www.arqtistic.com/fx(haish) to generate your “fx(haish) - The AI City” based on your mint. You have 20 tries.
Step 3. Await further instructions.


// FURTHER INFO

This algorithm has been designed to produce images which are suitable for the subsequent AI generation. The token consists of a random number of randomly placed and sized rectangles, filled with a noise gradient pattern. In short, Diffusion AI Models thrive on noise.

The AI generation uses Stable Diffusion 1.5 through an API designed by the 330ai team (@Pixelmindai). The WebUI has been developed by Nik0gda (@AntonCebanu2). AI Prompt has been designed (by me) to produce images of Cities, but you can possibly make it do other things, if you try hard enough.

metadata.name: This is Not an Image #4
metadata.description:
When you see a piece of generative art, you are looking at a meta-message, an image whose value is not of form but of subtext. These images are a collision and reformation of ideas and conceptual histories between artists Nudoru and Sub Net. This dichotomy reminds us of the painting "The Treachery of Images" by René Magritte, where he paints a picture of a pipe but states underneath, "ceci n'est pas une pipe" (This is not a pipe), meaning that there is a schism between what a thing is and what it represents. What is unique about these works go beyond the images and text combinations themselves. It is about how images create new thoughts not by not pretending to be completely novel but that builds upon one another in a system of complex synthesis.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press' p' to pause/resume.
Press' s' to save a screenshot. The image size is 2357 × 3000px.

Copyright (c) 2023 Matt Perkins (@nudoru) and Sub Net (@whoissubnet). Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: How to Draw Bubbles (◕‿◕)♡ #148
metadata.description:
[The solidness or volume of the form could be obtained by using highlights on one side of each object and shading on the opposite side.]


(⊃｡•́‿•̀｡)⊃━━━━☆


With only a few colorful lines near the edges and bright accents in the oposite corners, one rounded polygon becomes a shiny and bright voluminous surface. It's easy! 

Look out for the FOMO keyboard key to unlock more variations.




Wishing you easy, light and bubbly 2023! 
(◕‿◕)♡
